Koninkrijk"},"en":{"28 August 1552–1628":"28 August 1552–1628","1546–Female":"1546–Deceased","1548–1551":"1548–1551","1551–1551":"1551–1551","1552–1628":"1552–1628","1556–Female":"1556–Deceased","1558–1564":"1558–1564","1573–Male":"1573–Deceased","1576–Female":"1576–Deceased","1580–Female":"1580–Deceased","1523–Male":"1523–Deceased","28 Aug 1552":"28 August 1552","1580":"1580","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1546":"1546","1600":"1600","1523":"1523","1556":"1556","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1576":"1576","1564":"1564","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","1573":"1573","1551":"1551","28 August 1552":"28 August 1552","1628":"1628","1548":"1548","Chislet, Kent, England":"Chislet, Kent, England",", , Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tayler","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Taylor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Taylor","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish: occupational name for a tailor, from Anglo-Norman French, Middle English <i>taillour</i> ‘tailor’ (Old French <i>tailleor</i>, <i>tailleur</i>; Late Latin <i>taliator</i>, from <i>taliare</i> ‘to cut’). The surname is extremely common in Britain and Ireland. In North America, it has absorbed equivalents from other languages, many of which are also common among Ashkenazic Jews, for example German   Schneider   and Hungarian   Szabo  . It is also very common among African Americans.","In some cases also an Americanized form of French   Terrien   ‘owner of a farmland’ or of its altered forms, such as   Therrien   and   Terrian  ."]}]},{"name":"Edmond","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Edmund  , now in quite frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":5,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":16,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":32,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":34,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":47,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":67,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pi